Models are very cheap in Django. You crate a new Django app, add models in ```models.py```. As the business logic becomes complex your models become fatter. After couple of weeks or months later your ```models.py``` contains thousands of lines of code which is difficult to manage. Here I have presented my simple steps to minimize this problem. The accompanying project code can be found at my GitHub [noticeboard](http://github.com/writefaruq/noticeboard) repo. ###Go with your business work-flow Software development is a running process, often done in an iterative fashion. Developers who join later in this process has little or no idea about the business process. So they often become stuck in tarcing the relationship among models. So the first step becomes study the business work flow. Take a paper and pencil or just use this firfox [pencil](http://pencil.evolus.vn/). Draw diagrams in whatever format you like. Here's an example. Let's imagine that we have an online ***notice board*** application where customers post adverts. The fictional business work flow looks like this- ![sample business work-flow](/static/img/blog/architect-your-django-app-fig1-workflow.png) Fig 1: Sample work-flow of an ad publishing site From our imaginary work flow we can extract the candidate Django models, such as: ```Customer, Admin, Ad, Invoice```. We can also find some of the necessary properties of these objects such as, ```Ad``` should have ```status```: inactive or live, invoice should have status: paid or unpaid etc. Let's think about the link among the models. First start from the model that has no dependency. For grouping the ads in a meaningful way we'd like to create a ```AdCategory``` model that should be indepedent of anything else 
	from django.db import models
	from django.contrib.auth.models import User

	class AdCategory(models.Model):
	""" Classifies Ads: mainly into Event, Service and Classifieds etc."""
		name = models.CharField(max_length=127)
		description = models.TextField()
		publish_rate = models.DecimalField(max_digits=7, decimal_places=2, default=0)
Now we can create our ``Customer`` and ``Ad`` model - 

	 class Customer(models.Model):
    	 """ Based on User Profile """
		user = models.ForeignKey(User)
		is_active = models.BooleanField(default=True)

	class Ad(models.Model):
    	"""That appears on our notice board"""
	    title = models.CharField(max_length=127, help_text="Give a short crisp title")
	    description = models.TextField(help_text="Provide a descripttion in 200 words")
	    category = models.ForeignKey(AdCategory)
	    created_at = models.DateTimeField(auto_now=True)
	    last_updated = models.DateTimeField(auto_now_add=True)
	    owner = models.ForeignKey(Customer)  #: who creates this
	    (INACTIVE, UNDER_REVIEW, APPROVED, LIVE, EXPIRED) = range(5)
	    STATUS_CHOICES = (
                      (INACTIVE, 'Inactive'),  # Not published yet
                      (UNDER_REVIEW, 'Under Review'),  # Not published yet
                      (APPROVED, 'Approved'),
                      (LIVE, 'Live'),  # Available online
                      (EXPIRED, 'Expired') # publish time is over
        )
	    status = models.SmallIntegerField(choices=STATUS_CHOICES, default=INACTIVE, editable=False)
Since we'd like to pass our ad to an approval process. Let's crate a ``PublishRequest`` and ```ApprovalManager`` models - 

        class ApprovalManager(models.Model):
	"""Who approves our Ad"""
	    	user = models.ForeignKey(User)
	    	is_active = models.BooleanField(default=True)

	class PublishRequest(models.Model):
	""" Records a request of publication of an Ad """
	    ad = models.ForeignKey(Ad)
	    start_from = models.DateTimeField()
	    publish_day = models.PositiveIntegerField(help_text="publishing period in days")
	    is_approved = models.BooleanField(default=False)
	    notes = models.TextField(blank=True, null=True)
	    signed_by = models.ForeignKey(ApprovalManager, blank=True, null=True)
	    signed_at = models.DateTimeField(auto_now_add=True)
By the chaining of our modles we can keep track of the dependency and reduce redundant links. As our work flow changes we can re-link these models accordingly. ###Visualize models using ```graph_models`` We can use Django's excellent management command ``graph_models`` which is a part of [django-command-extensions](http://code.google.com/p/django-command-extensions/wiki/GraphModels) package. This can give us nice looking diagrams of our models. ![Admanager models shown by graph_models](/static/img/blog/architect-your-django-app-fig2-admanager.png) Fig 2: Admanager models shown by graph_models ###Find the link of relations -- A Layered Approach From the workflow and diagrams we can easily layer our model into three logical layers: 1. **Input Layer:** where input information is given, such as ``AdCategory, Ad`` 2. **Processing Layer:** where some processing happens such as: ``PublishRequest`` 3. **Output Layer:** where final output of processing is placed, say creating ``Invoice`` model (which is not shown here). This bottom-up stacking can be helpful to minimize mess and duplicating information in several models. ###Spilt your ```model.py``` So initialy we'd like to keep these models inside a same app. But later we'd see it's better to make a separate app for managing customer account balances and payments. ###Test and simulate The consitency among our designed models can be checked by writing unit tests. For example, we can create a scenario where an existing customer creates an ad and upon completing the work-flow, this ad's status become live.

Models are very cheap in Django. You crate a new Django app, add models in models.py. As the business logic becomes complex your models become fatter. After couple of weeks or months later your models.py contains thousands of lines of code which is difficult to manage. Here I have presented my simple steps to minimize this problem. The accompanying project code can be found at my GitHub noticeboard repo.

Go with your business work-flow

Software development is a running process, often done in an iterative fashion. Developers who join later in this process has little or no idea about the business process. So they often become stuck in tarcing the relationship among models.

So the first step becomes study the business work flow. Take a paper and pencil or just use this firfox pencil. Draw diagrams in whatever format you like. Here's an example.

Let's imagine that we have an online notice board application where customers post adverts. The fictional business work flow looks like this-

Fig 1: Sample work-flow of an ad publishing site

From our imaginary work flow we can extract the candidate Django models, such as: Customer, Admin, Ad, Invoice. We can also find some of the necessary properties of these objects such as, Ad should have status: inactive or live, invoice should have status: paid or unpaid etc.

Let's think about the link among the models. First start from the model that has no dependency. For grouping the ads in a meaningful way we'd like to create a AdCategory model that should be indepedent of anything else

    from django.db import models
    from django.contrib.auth.models import User

class AdCategory(models.Model):
    """ Classifies Ads: mainly into Event, Service and Classifieds etc."""
        name = models.CharField(max_length=127)
        description = models.TextField()
        publish_rate = models.DecimalField(max_digits=7, decimal_places=2, default=0)

Now we can create our Customer and Ad model - 


class Customer(models.Model):
         """ Based on User Profile """
        user = models.ForeignKey(User)
        is_active = models.BooleanField(default=True)

class Ad(models.Model):
        """That appears on our notice board"""
        title = models.CharField(max_length=127, help_text="Give a short crisp title")
        description = models.TextField(help_text="Provide a descripttion in 200 words")
        category = models.ForeignKey(AdCategory)
        created_at = models.DateTimeField(auto_now=True)
        last_updated = models.DateTimeField(auto_now_add=True)
        owner = models.ForeignKey(Customer)  #: who creates this
        (INACTIVE, UNDER_REVIEW, APPROVED, LIVE, EXPIRED) = range(5)
        STATUS_CHOICES = (
                      (INACTIVE, 'Inactive'),  # Not published yet
                      (UNDER_REVIEW, 'Under Review'),  # Not published yet
                      (APPROVED, 'Approved'),
                      (LIVE, 'Live'),  # Available online
                      (EXPIRED, 'Expired') # publish time is over
        )
        status = models.SmallIntegerField(choices=STATUS_CHOICES, default=INACTIVE, editable=False)

Since we'd like to pass our ad to an approval process. Let's crate a PublishRequest and `ApprovalManager models -


class ApprovalManager(models.Model):
    """Who approves our Ad"""
            user = models.ForeignKey(User)
            is_active = models.BooleanField(default=True)

class PublishRequest(models.Model):
    """ Records a request of publication of an Ad """
        ad = models.ForeignKey(Ad)
        start_from = models.DateTimeField()
        publish_day = models.PositiveIntegerField(help_text="publishing period in days")
        is_approved = models.BooleanField(default=False)
        notes = models.TextField(blank=True, null=True)
        signed_by = models.ForeignKey(ApprovalManager, blank=True, null=True)
        signed_at = models.DateTimeField(auto_now_add=True)

By the chaining of our modles we can keep track of the dependency and reduce redundant links. As our work flow changes we can re-link these models accordingly.

Visualize models using `graph_models

We can use Django's excellent management command graph_models which is a part of django-command-extensions package. This can give us nice looking diagrams of our models.

Fig 2: Admanager models shown by graph_models

Find the link of relations -- A Layered Approach

From the workflow and diagrams we can easily layer our model into three logical layers:

  1. Input Layer: where input information is given, such as AdCategory, Ad
  2. Processing Layer: where some processing happens such as: PublishRequest
  3. Output Layer: where final output of processing is placed, say creating Invoice model (which is not shown here).

This bottom-up stacking can be helpful to minimize mess and duplicating information in several models.

Spilt your model.py

So initialy we'd like to keep these models inside a same app. But later we'd see it's better to make a separate app for managing customer account balances and payments.

Test and simulate

The consitency among our designed models can be checked by writing unit tests. For example, we can create a scenario where an existing customer creates an ad and upon completing the work-flow, this ad's status become live.

            is_active = models.BooleanField(default=True)

class PublishRequest(models.Model):
    """ Records a request of publication of an Ad """
        ad = models.ForeignKey(Ad)
        start_from = models.DateTimeField()
        publish_day = models.PositiveIntegerField(help_text="publishing period in days")
        is_approved = models.BooleanField(default=False)
        notes = models.TextField(blank=True, null=True)
        signed_by = models.ForeignKey(ApprovalManager, blank=True, null=True)
        signed_at = models.DateTimeField(auto_now_add=True)

By the chaining of our modles we can keep track of the dependency and reduce redundant links. As our work flow changes we can re-link these models accordingly.

Visualize models using `graph_models

We can use Django's excellent management command graph_models which is a part of django-command-extensions package. This can give us nice looking diagrams of our models.

Fig 2: Admanager models shown by graph_models

Find the link of relations -- A Layered Approach

From the workflow and diagrams we can easily layer our model into three logical layers:

  1. Input Layer: where input information is given, such as AdCategory, Ad
  2. Processing Layer: where some processing happens such as: PublishRequest
  3. Output Layer: where final output of processing is placed, say creating Invoice model (which is not shown here).

This bottom-up stacking can be helpful to minimize mess and duplicating information in several models.

Spilt your model.py

So initialy we'd like to keep these models inside a same app. But later we'd see it's better to make a separate app for managing customer account balances and payments.

Test and simulate

The consitency among our designed models can be checked by writing unit tests. For example, we can create a scenario where an existing customer creates an ad and upon completing the work-flow, this ad's status become live.
